description:
LocalAPIGateway.handleChatCompletions() (Sources/LocalMgr/Services/LocalAPIGateway.swift, in the model-conflict/wake-up block) currently does:

    runner.startModel(matched)
    for _ in 0..<30 {
        if runner.status == .running { break }
        try? await Task.sleep(nanoseconds: 500_000_000)
    }

This is a crude fixed 15-second poll loop (30 x 500ms) with two problems:

1. No failure detail: if the model fails to start (wrong binary path, port conflict, crash on launch, etc.), the loop just times out silently and falls through to whatever check comes next (currently the 'no runner active' 503 guard), which reports a generic 'no local model runner is active' error rather than surfacing why the wake-up actually failed (e.g. the specific LocalMgrError the runner itself may have already recorded via BackendRunnerManager's own error path).
2. No adaptive/configurable timeout: 15 seconds may be too short for a large model on a cold page-cache (first load after reboot) and unnecessarily long for a small model that's ready in under a second -- it's a flat sleep-and-poll with no early-exit on a definitive failure signal (e.g. runner.status == .error) either, so a fast failure still burns the full 15s before the gateway responds.

This is adjacent to localmgr-jhj.7's startup-phase-callback work (DaemonStartupPhase enum, health-poll loop) but scoped specifically to the gateway's on-demand wake path rather than the UI's model-launch status display. Once jhj.7 lands a proper phase-callback/AsyncStream during engine start, this gateway polling loop should consume that same signal (awaiting the ready phase or a failed(String) phase) instead of polling runner.status in a fixed loop, and surface a specific LocalMgrError (kind: gateway-wake-timeout or similar) with whatever detail is available (e.g. the last few TailBuffer log lines from jhj.5) rather than falling through to the generic 'no runner active' 503.

Discovered while reviewing the gateway code during the localmgr-al0/localmgr-ae9/localmgr-mtz bug-fixing session -- not itself a confirmed live bug (no live repro), but a design gap noticed by inspection that becomes directly actionable once jhj.7's phase-callback plumbing exists.

Add 5 new @AppStorage(Bool) properties to AppSettings, one per EngineType case, keyed by the Swift enum case name (not the display-string rawValue, so a future rawValue/display-string change never silently resets a user's toggle): 
  @AppStorage("engineEnabled.llamaCpp") var engineEnabledLlamaCpp: Bool = true
  @AppStorage("engineEnabled.mlx") var engineEnabledMLX: Bool = true
  @AppStorage("engineEnabled.liteRT") var engineEnabledLiteRT: Bool = true
  @AppStorage("engineEnabled.kokoro") var engineEnabledKokoro: Bool = false
  @AppStorage("engineEnabled.gemmaCpp") var engineEnabledGemmaCpp: Bool = false
Add `func isEngineEnabled(_ engine: EngineType) -> Bool` (switches over the 5 properties) and `func setEngineEnabled(_ engine: EngineType, _ value: Bool)` so call sites (Settings UI, EngineReadinessService, BackendRunnerManager) never need a 5-way switch of their own.

Files: Sources/LocalMgr/Models/AppSettings.swift.
